<BaseLayout
  title="AI in Practice training — grimbergIT"
  description="Hands-on AI training for professional software teams — the boring wins and the boundaries."
>
  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Workshop · 05</p>
    <h1>AI in Practice</h1>

    <p>
      Not the "here is a nice prompt" kind of session. This workshop is hands-on with the tools your
      team already has: Copilot, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT. I focus on the wins that don't look
      impressive on LinkedIn, and on the boundaries around when <em>not</em> to hand it the keys.
    </p>

    <h2>What we cover</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Pair-programming with an AI assistant that doesn't lie to you: the prompt shape that matters
        and the review discipline that makes it safe.
      </li>
      <li>
        Code review as a second pair of eyes — catching the boring bugs humans miss, without
        outsourcing the judgement.
      </li>
      <li>
        Test generation: where it saves time (unit-level scaffolding, table-driven cases) and where
        it creates false confidence.
      </li>
      <li>
        Documentation and refactor prep — the workflows AI is quietly excellent at, and where most
        teams under-use it.
      </li>
      <li>
        Boundaries: what to keep out of prompts, what to keep humans in the loop for, and how to
        write down the rules your team will actually follow.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>
      One day by default. Splittable into two half-days if the team's calendar prefers it. Also
      available as a multi-session cohort if you want to work AI into everyday practice over several
      weeks.
    </p>

    <h2>What you leave with</h2>
    <p>
      A short internal playbook — what you'll use AI for, what you won't, and where the seams are —
      plus a set of workflows the team has actually tried, not just heard about.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/training/">← Back to training</a> ·
      <a href="/contact">Book a session →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
